{"text": "Life is Strange, is quite safe to say is a modern day favourite among many gamers throughout the globe. It was released in 2015 designed by DontNod Entertainment and produced by Square Enix Studios. It is the first among the four games which are set in the Life is Strange Universe, thus acting as the launching pad for an incredible gaming franchise. It’s one of a kind game which follows a new style of storytelling combined with a hell lot of fun quests and some really deep and emotional moments leaving a sense of satisfaction on a player's mind. It’s a game where choices, however small they seem will have major consequences in the end, potentially filling the player with guilt for the decisions which were not taken or which simply felt irrelevant earlier. The game kicks off with Max finding herself nearby a lighthouse in Arcadia Bay while one monstrous tornado is headed to destroy the city. Desperate to find shelter she moves towards this lighthouse and then out of nowhere a boat comes across flying and hits it. Seemingly watching her death, Max’s vision abruptly ends and she finds herself in Mr Jefferson's class.  Overwhelmed and confused by this crazy vision she seeks some space in girl’s washroom. Moments later we are introduced with Nathan Prescott and a punk girl who is trying to blackmail him. Things go sideways and Nathan ends her life .Max hiding and watching everything can’t stand the killing and tries to intervene. Suddenly, as if time rewinds itself and in the very next second she was back in the same class she attended 15 minutes ago.  Bewildered by this event she observes and compares the flow of events and to her shock she did time travel somehow. Back in time, the thought of saving the poor girl comes to her mind and she jets off to the washroom and saves her by tripping off the fire alarm. Nathan confronts Max about the washroom incident and just when things were getting violent she is rescued by Chloe, her best friend and the same girl whom she saved. Following up some sentimental really likeable set of interactions involving all major characters, which involves interesting acts like Max proving her abilities to Chloe and an undesirable meeting with a drug dealer the focus then shifts on investigating Rachel's whereabouts and finding evidence to support Kate Marsh's (a sweet and pure girl who got dragged into a situation she never wanted) dire case. For this cause they break into Blackwell during curfew hours, steal David's personal investigation and dissect Frank Bower's customer log. Combining all the scattered evidence they find something really heart breaking and disturbing which i can’t write for the sake of *spoilers*.  During the course of these events Max had to use her powers to save and change a lot of lives, for better or for worse. Even needing to go back in time several times to change and create new timelines. The noticeable point here is this that in all these different timelines a common fate awaits for Max and Chloe which is stubborn and unshakable.  Leaving a question whether they should stop trying and accept their fate. This revelation left both of them shocked, furious and devastated. Thus, beginning a circle of events which is too much for any teenager to fight. The beauty of this game is how effortless it is to connect with the story and characters reminding us of our own childhood's complicated friendships and how difficult it could be for a teenager these days. There is sea of emotions waiting to be ridden behind the friendship of two former best friends. Players get to play as Max Caulfield in a third person environment through five different episodes across the playable areas of Blackwell Academy, Two Whales Diner and Chloe's room to name a few. The game basically needs players to interact with people ad various different objects like flyers, letters, car keys etc. present in an area allowing Max to retrieve necessary information to complete her missions. These missions are not possible to complete without her rewind power, which allows her to go back in time and use the info she gained in her last conversation to find clues in a newer never happened conversation. Throughout the game Max will have the opportunity to snap some cool shots which are optional and each individual shot is a steam achievement. There is an option to replay an episode in collectible mode where the choices taken are not affected and is specifically designed to complete the achievements set. There are also some nice puzzles to solve during the course of the game which needs clever use of Max's rewind to get a few things in order to solve them. Not to forget the optional choice to help random people around her by bending time and which does have some effect on the final outcome in future. The most awesome and at the same time the craziest of Max’s abilities is to actually send her consciousness to a younger self of hers by just focusing on a photograph. This allows her to change events in the past and alter the future into a completely new one. The photograph or as said by Mr Jefferson, “The pieces of time\" carry their literal meaning when it comes to our protagonist. The visuals of Life is Strange is presented in a completely new format which uses the water colour art featured models and environment. The characters seem to be out of a 3-Dimensional art book and the environments out of a painting. This new style of presentation is really lovely and light for the eyes for a change. The cut scenes and time rewinding sequences are well detailed and there are plenty of beautiful frames throughout the game which are perfect for capturing screenshots. The various planes of reality, the monstrous tornado and the beautiful Arcadia Bay beach are some of the beautifully designed visuals. The only addressable down point in graphics is a point in the game where the background dialogue is in play but the lips show no movement. Apart from this the graphics is really well done where every face shows the exact emotion which is needed at the right moment. The sounds and music department for life is Strange is terrific and sublime. The playback songs are very carefully selected and played at the right portions of the game which are soothing to listen to and can sometimes get very sentimental. It adds an extra punch to the game whenever a moving and deep sequence is in play or gives enough elating feeling when it’s a light comic moment. The voice acting for every character behind the scenes is well done; the dialogues are really intriguing making the characters more relatable to the player. Every character is in sync with the voice behind them. The subtle sound of the birds chirping or the loud and soul scaring noise of the tornado comes out really well. Thus, making it a complete visual and auditory experience. Life is Strange brings forward the concept of fighting an inevitable destiny form happening to a very special person in the protagonist's life and at the same time it brilliantly portrays the struggles of today's youth. It asks our hero how far they are willing to go loading the consequences of her actions on her tiny shoulders. It’s a journey or a journey in several alternate timelines to change a single thing from happening, on which a great many people's lives hinges on. A true masterpiece where it is upon the player to make the final tough call.......", "appid": "319630", "steamid": "profiles/76561198137364421", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "13", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1539432000.0}
