{"text": "Aragami  Lince Works  Lince Works  Action-adventure, stealth  Unity  4 Oct, 2016  Single-player, multi-player The moment you open Aragami's main menu and hear that tranquil theme playing in an ornamental background having the moon shimmering behind the dark peculiar protagonist, you will immediately commingle with its charming atmosphere. What this game does the best is making you feel like a real 死神 tearing through waves of enemies through a flawless path painted by your bloodlust. Although this may fill your adrenaline to the optimal level, don't expect any clashing hack and slash combat. Candidly, this game follows the 忍術 modus operandi; a single slip up is an instant 死—shinobis' gaffes are fatal. In Aragami, you are an 荒神, a vengeful spirit, who was conjured by Yamiko—an ethereal looking woman—to help her escape from imprisonment by the Kaiho. The tale seems very simple, but the twist and turns that happen within it while you go deeper in the rabbit hole fuel your interest in digging even more. I didn't like the method utilized in the communication between the characters in the game. The conversation between the characters is in the Swedish language but reversed and scrambled to create vexatious, gibberish sounds that sound like the Japanese language. Its main goal is to give you something to hear while reading the written dialogue between the characters. One of the protuberant UI elements in Aragami is the heads-up display that is integrated into the character's model. The playable character's cape has all the HUD elements you need for immersive gameplay. It's fabricated artistically, but it can be a bit huckery when deformed, and in certain quandaries, it can get exasperating to extract required deets from it. The gameplay core aspect is designed to encourage the clandestine playstyle; whether you plan in being a Shinigami, specter, or benevolent, you don't want to get caught so as to avoid messy situations. Using direct encounters as a strategy for killstreaks in Aragami is arduous; if you kill an enemy near another alerted enemy, consider yourself dead due to long executive animations that pause your control of the main character. The way the game presents its contrast of being hidden and vulnerable is cool; while hidden, the entire screen goes dark meaning that you are out of sight, and the other case is vice versa. The teleporting technique plays a major role in your gameplay, and it's amplified by the utilitarian skills that can be unlocked in your playthrough. Some of them encourage the stealthy pacifist style while the other serves a lethal approach. Teleporting from a shadowy spot to another is fluid, but sometimes it can get annoying to slip from the desired location due to unintentional slight movement of the mouse. The inclusion of a proper cover system would have been much appreciated; this could enhance the overall experience and enable us to scout efficiently without compromising our location. The method the game uses to increase the difficulty is about quantity rather than quality; in other words, it will throw more morons in the map to make it overcrowded with cretinous AI. From a visual scope, the game art style is captivating, but unfortunately, the texture quality is barely mediocre; some areas in the game feel dull and not detailed. This made me concerned that there is a problem with the game's files or with its settings, but eventually, I concluded that it's the game's level of graphical quality. The enemies' variety is the least to expect in Aragami. The game also suffers from various bugs that can be very frustrating; bugs like falling from the ground plane, getting stuck in a tight place while teleporting, UI issues, etc. One of the most frustrating bugs was when I played a challenging level on the hardest difficulty, and after completion, it strangely mentions that I've finished it on the normal difficulty; this happened to me 3 times. The game's port is below average at best, and what makes the matter even worse is that it isn't that demanding, so any lagging or FPS drops are not acceptable. The soundtrack is very fitting and blends magnificently with the game's mood and events. I won't cover the multiplayer of this game, since I didn't try it, but I think it has the potential to be enjoyable, provided that the contributing players understand each other quite well. Despite its flaws, I love Aragami. An exceptional soundtrack, a ravishing art style that overclouds the lackluster textures, beautifully designed main characters, wonderful gameplay, and a good story: all these combine to form a remarkable experience. Sadly, the overall poor technical quality of the game hurts it badly. I hope to see more of Lince Works, and I sincerely admire their delightful work, and the effort they put in this game.", "appid": "280160", "steamid": "profiles/76561198144671880", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "29", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1593172800.0}
