{"text": "Opening an old, dusty box in the attic, coughing like hell and getting your eyes irritated due to the suffocating, aged dust contained within. It has been years, if not decades, when you laid your eyes upon that once silver coloured box and the many games received as gifts, probably, amongst the many iconic titles, one always stood up to you, maybe it was the hype, maybe it was how the story sparked interest or maybe, just maybe it's the pointy... ''triangles''. Nonetheless, you pick up everything, run down the stairs, plug everything correctly and fire the beast already. Damn... 24 years has passed and it still smells like childhood.                                                        Contracted under a fancy businesswoman’s greed, our archeologist and professional adventurer, Lara Croft, embarks in an exciting adventure to discover and uncover the mysteries on her journey about pieces of the artifact Scion by any means necessary, even if it leads to some bodies and casings dropping by her iconic pistols...                                                     ''Tomb Raider I'' is a pixelated, adventure and action packed game, a mixture between acrobatics and puzzles with a pinch of violence since that's how everything works in archeology. Being the PC version, it uses DosBox, an IBM PC emulator for the game to run on most modern computers and supporting 3Dfx, a 3D graphics processing card, unlike the console versions, it features differences between one and another both in terms of visuals and gameplay.  About controls, it definitely feels clunky while the sensitivity is responsive in a good way but the reaction time between the combinations of some buttons can be annoying at times, for example, trying to jump from one ledge to another, moving blocks, etc. Also, there isn't any possibility for you to change controls neither the emulator supports a console controller base for those who desires the real nostalgic experience. In terms of AI, it executes the job right throughout the variety of enemies along the gameplay, most being animals and mythical creatures, even if some bugs may occur, especially with a particular flying type and since I mentioned this is an action game, of course there’s a small arsenal for the combat, possessing double handguns at the beginning but later obtaining a pump shotgun, double magnums and double Uzis.   Along the journey, you will mostly notice the details present on the levels as well as the diversity between the locations portrayed in the game whether it being Atlantis’s grotesque, living walls  or Egypt’s hieroglyphics on the walls filled with a variety of traps and hidden secrets with some awards awaiting to be found in the levels, it is a pixel game with the iconic drawn distance obscuring what lurks ahead making it more mysterious and adventurous although for those who are aware, the PC version has a limited number of the soundtracks unlike the consoles, this is the music to highlight certain areas in the levels, due to limit data on the CD so the only thing playing is some repetitive ambient noises throughout the gameplay.  Before the sequel came out in 1997, ‘’Tomb Raider Gold: Unfinished business’’ was made and published which included 2 chapters, 2 levels for each, set in Egypt and Atlantis but unfortunately this isn’t included neither in Steam’s stores nor Steam’s achievements are available.                                              In this gameplay, honestly, I couldn’t find anything game breaking, except pressing the desktop button and considering the emulator, even the Steam overlay is interfering the game's menu and sometimes blocks the controls, in the console versions, most preferably the PS1, there is a famous bug involving the main protagonist jumping continuously on a certain part of a ledge or corner making the character instantly teleport to any floor above, helpful to skip large portions of the game, tried this one but didn't work and also some of the enemies has some issues, in the level ‘’Cistern’’ there are hidden rats in the underwater parts at the beginning as well as other issues in other levels.                                                         In my early days of gaming with the PS1, I remember playing ‘’Tomb Raider I’’ amongst the next titles of the series and I can definitely say it was one of the best times of my life as a kid discovering these types of technology.  After playing this port, I can guarantee a huge difference more in the visuals than the gameplay and for start, the controls is not one of my personal favorite because the console controller feels more natural for me than the keyboard in this game and so far I can’t find the keyword to look around the area, toughening a bit the difficulty, nevertheless, it didn’t quite bother me later besides mixing up the buttons and leading the main character to her death in some occasions, most during fights. While I am mentioning this, the combat system is good, I like it, it isn’t based on the difficulty but rather the enemy you’re against in which the enemies will vary and become faster and aggressive throughout the levels, additionally, the arsenal’s usefulness is cool and fun, however, I have a doubt about the ammunition lying around, specifically the Uzis and magnums, when picked up it only shows ‘’2 magnum rounds/Uzi rounds’’ but when acquiring the weapons, it would multiply the ammo by more than hundreds, depending on how much you picked up at the beginning.  Everybody loves astonishing graphics, beautiful visuals and an immersive game and ‘’Tomb Raider I’’ fits this category for its decade and for the years ahead, but nowadays? It still is interesting for its visuals and surprisingly it was updated throughout the ports for better rendering graphics and performance, comparing the PS1 with the PC and 3Dfx, there is a significant difference from a faster performance to its good filtered colours and overall a great rendered visuals surrounding the player, not only that but the puzzles were quite lovely to do including with the exploring as well as the sneaky traps in some levels and the limited soundtracks? Definitely impacting while blasting everything with the pistols, what I didn’t liked was the cutscenes, it looked horrible and I’m not sure if it was the dimension of the screen or some issue related with my PC which is something that I loved watching as a kid in this game.  The big question, would I recommend it? Absolutely, long answer? This was the beginning of a great series that made a big impact in the videogame industry when the sequel came out, as some of you might know, it definitely brought me some memories of playing it even if I genuinely wasn’t expecting the visual differences and the fact of a limited soundtracks and the cutscenes making me a bit disappointed and in case for those who wants to improve more than it already is, there is a dedicated community providing everything however from my point, I think the player should enjoy the default game without modifying it, this truly is a gem from the past and I think everybody should give it a go. Score: 7.5/10", "appid": "224960", "steamid": "profiles/76561198823468150", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "58", "votes_funny": "3", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1595160000.0}
