{"text": "A personal favorite, Bioshock Infinite maintains strong gameplay, story elements, and writing. While not particularly deep, the story includes many interesting themes, making the player consider of the pros and cons of American idealism, segregation, evangelist beliefs, and the divide between low and high class social templates. This makes the story rather engaging, however when the game dives into strange and unrealistic quantum mechanics, it kills the immersion into the well constructed 1910's world. The gameplay never gets old, as the gunplay is quite polished, several tonics (essentially superpowers) scatter the world introducing a whole new side to combat, and the inclusion of skylines (hanging rails that you may jump onto during combat) all ensure a diverse combat experience that never grows stale. Elizabeth and Booker (the main characters) are very well written, and undergo plenty of character development as the the game goes on. This game is fantastic, and I reccomend anyone even partially interigued in this game to purchase it. I can assure it will not dissapoint.", "appid": "8870", "steamid": "profiles/76561198056526892", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1483617600.0}
