{"text": "Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly is a Visual Novel developed by IDEA FACTORY and published by INTRAGAMES. It's a work of art, enriched even more so by captivating storytelling, unexpected plot twists and detailed and breathtaking art style. While the first chapters might seem dull and not as promising, it doesn't take long before we can get into the core narrative. Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly offers six possible love interests but doesn't really focus too much on the \"Otome\" aspect, rather in fixing something that in each main character has been broken, and stolen. The narration begins with the protagonist waking up all alone and with no memories regarding herself, in a seemingly lonesome and abandoned manor. Navigating in the story through the Flowchart, it's up to us to find out why she's been locked up in a never-ending nightmare.      • Immersive and engrossing storyline • Captivating, in-depth characters • Well thought character development • Amazing art and fitting OST      • The game crashes.. a lot          As I've mentioned beforehand, Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly could seem like a hard game to fully appreciate or get into, mainly due to a slow and quite clichè start. You wake up in a world you have no recollection of, with little to no memories about yourself, not even what your name might be and what you had been doing prior to finding yourself in a frightening dark mansion.  Amnesia is a concept that has been widely explored in the Visual Novels genre, but is amnesia all there is to the main character losing her memories? There's a bigger mystery that has enveloped the manor in a neverending bittersweet embrace, and it is up to us, and the companions we ally with for the task, to find out what is truly going on. The only hint being \"Complete the kaleidoscope\". Particularly remarkable in Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly is the protagonist, Beniyuri. It's rare to have a MC with as much personality and character as she does, of course, she's not immune to the grim events of the dark manor, but she's not a pushover and she'll have everyone know that well enough the more we delve into the story.  The interactions between our MC and the male love interests are always either funny and sweet, through the numerous friendly banters scattered throughout the storyline and in the special unlockable short episodes, or sad and bittersweet. Although the latter highly outnumbers the first. After all, Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly is not a happy tale, and it's something to keep in mind when considering whether or not to buy the game. Hidden behind a facade of pretty male interests and sweet moments crowned with gorgeous CGs, there's a story that is full of sorrow, regret, and remorse. The desire of escaping reality due to a terrible event that has haunted our MC ever since it took place. This push and pull between despair and hope is a theme that highly appealed to me, thanks to a beautifully written tale that doesn't merely narrate events from the MC's point of view but gives you the means of experiencing the truth through other characters' eyes. Thanks to the Flowchart, we're free to navigate through the chapters and experience the story following different choices than the ones we had previously chosen. This opens up the possibility of going through 12 different endings, all of them with a strong original imprint that doesn't make them any less important than the main \"Best Ending\".  It may come to your attention that in the Flowchart, alongside the storyline development, there will be some unlockable short episodes, most of the time required to either process through the story, or to unlock a specific character's ending. To unlock such episodes, we must play a mini-game that, thanks to the story's plot itself, fits well enough in the context and isn't too annoying to replay. It's a short shooter mini-game, in which we're tasked to \"defend\" ourselves from the Black Butterflies. The more combos you're able to cash in during the mini-game, the more points you're given in order to unlock the short episodes. The Flowchart per se makes playing through Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly a lot easier, especially for those that might want to go for a 100% completion of the game. Jumping back effortlessly to important decisions saves you the trouble of replaying through a story that would otherwise be more than 15~ hours worth. Alongside a great storyline there just had to be an equally great cast. The characters' emotions and feelings aren't left out of the picture, instead, they are depicted in a way that would make the reader feel exactly what they are feeling. None of the characters in Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly are who they seem to be at first, and every and each of them is hiding their demons deep inside their hearts, locked away with forgotten memories. None of our beloved characters are \"static\" or \"unmoving\": they have desires, hopes, and dreams. Each of them is an important pawn in the wicked dimension they are thrown in. Through denial, guilt, remorse, and self-blaming the characters in the game are an almost pitch-perfect representation of how humans cope with pain, suffering, and loss. It's probably thanks to this incredibly human-like side of the characters that our attachment to them greatly increases the more we delve into the narration.       Featuring 12 possible endings, Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly offers between 20 and 30 hours of gameplay, although it very much depends on how fast of a reader you are. The Flowchart system makes navigating through the content even faster than it would normally be in any other Visual Novel.           The first thing I noticed about this VN, I'll admit, was the artwork. The sprites are superb, drawn with meticulous attention to details and all the possible facial expressions. The CGs are quite frequent and the closeness between the MC and the other characters in those makes up for the lack of in-depth romance.      The voice acting in this game just left me absolutely awestruck. \"Perfect\" doesn't even begin to describe it. I'm pretty sure I've never felt the characters' emotions come through the VA in such an impactful way as I've experienced with Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly.      I have lost count of how many times I've had to restart the game due to the all too frequent crashes. There doesn't seem to be a fix as of yet.     Psychedelica of the Black Butterfly is, in conclusion, truly a gem in the Visual Novel genre, and one that has seemingly gone by quite unnoticed or received bad rating for all the wrong reasons. It's a bittersweet game that you should be venturing in without high hopes for in-depth romance routes but expecting, on the other hand, one of the most endearing tales that the Visual Novel genre has to offer. It's not for everyone, and if you're looking for something cheerful and uplifting, you should definitely avoid this for the time being.", "appid": "865820", "steamid": "profiles/76561198108015755", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "44", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1542715200.0}
