{"text": "This game is like a masterclass in (architectural) level design with its origins firmly rooted in immersive sims, meaning: the versatility to play the game the way you seem fit under mostly 3 different playstyles of 'Ghosting', 'Action' or 'Non-Lethal', or a combination hereof in which case the game really excels in offering the player a huge variety of gameplay options where usually when you play through a game once, you're kind of done with it but with Dishonored you kind of 'always' have something new to come back to because of the way that the game is designed and at least in terms of achievements which are fun and engaging it will keep you interested if nothing else motivate the player to perhaps consider a multiple-playthrough solution to get them all because some of them are really interesting and usually flow well with the game, depending on your play-style. Game's engine is switched up from Dishonored 1 which used Unreal Engine (3 I believe) with now being a custom made 90% modified ID-Tech engine (From games like Doom 3 and Wolfenstein games most notably) called 'Void' which in terms of the game itself has better level of detail in the levels themselves as well as general aesthetics. Personally I really like this change and hence why I mention it but need to make one remark in this regard, and that is that the game unless set to full-high video options is kind of blurry which persists throughout whole of the game experience where before with Dishonored 1 I didn't have this problem but also wasn't more ugly as a game necessarily. I like to play with high frames and in this case it meant that i had to turn the graphics settings down to medium-low in order to have a constant 144FPS with my 1080, this next to the blurrieness that is existent unless you've got the game turned up to Ultra settings, makes for a bit getting used to but this isn't the game's fault necessarily. I really like the game very much, fact that you can play via either Emily or Corvo gives reason to adjust your playstyle each playthrough you do but with certain limiting factors that I feel are like design choices in regards to amount of levels in game for instance (each Dishonored game has 'only' 9 levels and they aren't varied sometimes, ea playing in same place or setting) really make me miss more of the games content but if you take the whole Triology of games into account then this notion becomes secondary and the more important aspects becomes the story itself in which case of these 3 games, has been up till now very cool. A very sort of mature game and deep one at that. Pity it didn't do too well to warrant more because it seems like it will die a silent death just like Thief-series of games did, although that one had a remake, it was good but not necessarily as the original which means: fingers crossed for the series as a whole. Dishonored games lend so much from other genres and games (sometimes literally) I feel that they themselves become unique experiences and are best approached like this, I think. Very immersive, fun and well flushed out experiences. Arkane Studios, job well done on delivering this Singleplayer awesomeness.", "appid": "403640", "steamid": "profiles/76561197988758568", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1596801600.0}
