{"text": "\"Deadly Premonition\" is an open-world murder mystery with horror elements. It features an interesting story with bizarre characters, action sequences that play like a slow third-person shooter, occasional easy puzzles. and a fairly large map to explore. Unfortunately the PC port is barely playable due to technical issues. The game successfully creates a \"US small-town\" environment with many characters who have their own schedules, and have different things to say depending on the current state of affairs. The murder mystery is exceptionally well designed - lots of people are suspect in one way or another, but there is no obvious culprit. You always feel that there is more to the murders than you already know, and the story ends in a chain of revelations that definitely surprised me. The main plot is very linear, but the game also offers 50 side quests, and you are usually free to decide which tasks you tackle next. The side quests are, however, often completely nonsensical and feel tacked-on. The FBI agent that you play, is a pretty interesting character (for example, he keeps talking to his partner that no one else can see, and uses his morning coffee as an oracle). However, he's also an arrogant jerk and a terrible chauvinist, he's very judgmental in his off-hand remarks about other people, and I didn't really feel comfortable playing him. I think he was intended to be a brilliant but emotionally challenged detective, but the writing was not good enough to pull that off. The writing - or perhaps rather the English translation - is unfortunately a problem for many characters and scenes throughout the game. Speakers often contradict themselves within just a few sentences, the flow of many conversations makes little sense, and it often feels as if lines were translated one by one without knowledge of the context.  Apart from exploring the map and talking to people, a substantial part of the game takes place in a surrealistically warped version of the town's environment where zombie-like creatures try to kill you. You fight back with a variety of guns and melee weapons while also looking for clues and helpful items. The fights are fairly easy as most of the enemies move slowly and/or in predictable patterns, but they are successful in creating an eerie, creepy atmosphere. Occasionally you run into harder boss encounters with QTE elements and multiple phases. The game provides ample room for exploration and generally rewards it with small amounts of money. There are also 65 collectibles to find. Graphics looked already dated when the game was originally released in 2010. They look crude and primitive by today's standards, but were still good enough to not affect my enjoyment. Unfortunately the PC port is locked to a 720p resolution, which means that you can see each individual pixel on a large monitor. It also uses a washed-out color palette, which many people see as a negative compared to the original Xbox version, but I think it actually fits the atmosphere quite well. Sound and music are competently done. The game contains some catchy, simple tunes that I liked, though they seemed much too upbeat for the atmosphere of the game. That said, they can be seen as providing welcome relaxation and relief between the more tense parts of the game. Much (but not all) of the dialogue is voiced, and the voice actors did a good job, though voice direction was clearly lacking - it's often obvious that the lines were delivered without knowledge of the context. Usability features are a mixed bag with this game. You can rebind action keys, but that's not very useful because movement is fixed to WASD. You can invert the Y- and even X-axis separately, and you can choose different settings for camera movement and aiming, but there's no FOV slider. You can save manually, but only at dedicated save spots, and there's only one save slot. The game's biggest problem by far are its technical issues. It kept crashing about once per 90 minutes on average, and while that can be mitigated by saving at each and every opportunity, that is a) not always possible, and b) detrimental to the experience when you keep worrying about finding a save spot rather than enjoying the story. One scene crashed every time it played, so I had to search forums for a workaround (which was, oddly enough, to let several hours of in-game time pass). Another problem is a perpetual loud screeching noise, accompanied by equally loud, high-pitched, frantic \"blip\" noises, whenever I was in a car (which amounts to many hours). Alt-tabbing out of the game caused it to freeze irrecoverably each and every time unless I was playing in windowed mode, but then I was limited to a 720p window. Two boss fights require you to turn off auto-aim (otherwise you _cannot_ hit your target), but auto-aim always gets automatically switched on whenever you draw a weapon, and turning it off requires a keypress that does not always work. There are community fixes for some of these issues, but they do not work for everyone. In short, this port is a terrible mess and it reflects badly on Rising Star games that they released this title in such a shoddy state without ever fixing it. I recommend Deadly Premonition for its complex plot, immersive setting, and bizarre characters. It definitely deserves its status as a cult classic. That said, be prepared for many painful moments due to the game's technical issues. If you're not willing to accept frequent crashes and multiple other issues (like that loud screeching noise whenever you're driving), you probably won't be able to enjoy this game. The Steam achievements show that 42% of players finished the prologue, but only 12% made it through the first quarter of the game, and my guess is that most players will just decide that the technical issues are too annoying to put up with. If you can get the game on Xbox, play it there, as all the ports have issues of some sort. If you get it on PC, wait for a steep sale and brace yourself for a rocky ride.", "appid": "247660", "steamid": "profiles/76561198025309409", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "12", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1595332800.0}
