{"text": "One of Ubisoft’s most critically acclaimed franchises; Far Cry 3 is regarded as a fan favourite for many. It also happens to be my first Far Cry game, and after finishing it, I can see why the game is held to high praise.  + From a visual stand point, the game has aged rather well. The islands are all varied and beautiful to explore. The actual size of the map is huge, containing biomes such as forests, mountains, vast planes etc. There are various settlements and historical points of interest, which are all interesting to explore as well. + The gun play also holds up pretty well. There is a massive variety of weapons that the player can use, however as soon as I got the bow and arrow, I didn’t really need much else. The combat can get pretty intense, and while it isn’t perfect, it doesn’t end up feeling repetitive.  + The story is really good. I had no idea what to expect from a Far Cry game in terms of narrative, and I was pleasantly surprised. The story revolves around two things; saving your friends, and insanity. It'll make sense when you play it. The second half of the story isn’t as good as the first half but it’s still engaging all the same. + The characters are one of the main highlights of this game for sure. The main character is alright. He’s a bit of a prat but he has his reasons for that. Some of the side characters such as Willis and Sam are great to be around. The best one though, without a doubt, is Vaas. He’s incredibly well written and acted. One of the best video game antagonists I’ve seen in a while. + As is usual with most Ubisoft games, the soundtrack is great. Brian Tyler’s “I’m Sorry” track in particular is an iconic one. The game utilises its soundtrack very well, whether it be the calm, placid radio tunes to the up-beat, exhilarating combat tracks. + Clearing out and securing outposts turned out to be quite fun due to the number of ways you can approach them. You can try stealth and mark your targets, taking them out one by one. You can go all in guns blazing. Or you can do a bit of both. The massive weapon variety gives you plenty of options.    + While I do have issues with some vehicles, the number of ways you can traverse the islands are immense. As well as the vast variety of cars, you can travel via speed boat, zip line, quad bike, glider, parachute and a jump suit. Or you can be lazy and fast travel but where’s the fun in that?  - The ending:  - The driving is pretty horrendous. To summarise, it feels like a clunky mess. Sometimes it felt like I was driving on ice. Turn slightly too much and you’ll end up on your side. Very fun. - Some of the mechanics feel clunky or really dated. They’re small things that still have an impact on the gameplay. For example, you need a prompt to be able to climb ledges. Any prompts in general are a bit hit or miss. If you’re on fire, you have to hold down Q to put it out. Q also happens to be the same button to use a health kit. Fall damage is also nuts. Jump down a small flight of stairs and there goes almost half your health.  - Inventory management feels very dated. There were plenty of times where I had no idea what I was looking at, and there were often times where I wasn’t sure how much of something I had. It’s confusing and messy. Despite its issues I had a very good time with Far Cry 3. It’s a game with a relatively simple concept that expands and gets more captivating the more you play it.  The game has a strong, compelling narrative, combined with interesting and well written characters. The iconic antagonists, such as Vaas, make the story a whole lot more memorable as well. The gameplay, while dated in some aspects, is still really engaging and fun to experience.  It’s far from perfect though. Most issues stem from the gameplay, something you learn to persevere through. The clunky mechanics don’t really become a bother until later on. At that point, some parts of the game will drag because of them.  While these issues are definitely a problem and do detract from the experience, Far Cry 3 still succeeds in being an iconic FPS that will continue to stand as one of Ubisoft’s greats. If you’re wanting to get into the franchise like I was, this game is a good place to start.", "appid": "220240", "steamid": "profiles/76561198091255120", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "10", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1600430400.0}
