{"text": "Dark Souls III (and the games before it) is a game that will be challenging, testing your patience but also makes you connect with the world and characters you find along the way. At the time you arrive in Lothric everything has already gone wrong, the Kingdom that once was has fallen from grace and the prince failed to fulfill his duty to link the fire. So it comes that 4 former champions of ash also refuse to link the first flame and thats where you get into the picture.  You are Ash because you already linked the fire in the past, but it would appear that your services are needed once more to \"save\" the kingdom. Which is where your journey begins.  You get to pick from a couple of different classes all varied in equipment, level, stats and spells you also get to pick a burial gift. Character creation has a lot of sliders and options and is very great at creating horrible abominations. The game offers a lot of options when it comes to playstyle, weaponry, magic (in form of pyromancy, sorcery and miracles), armor, rings and usable items with different effects.  Combat on the surface is pretty straight forward, you have a light attack and a heavy attack, the former using less stamina then the latter. Stamina being the resource you have to perform moves like sprinting, attacking and dodging (all of which you will be doing a lot of) so its fair to say that you should keep an eye on that.  New to Dark Souls III's combat system are weapon arts, some of which are unique and some aren't (unique weapons have a higher probability to have a unique weapon art). Although you need to be careful during travels, its still in your best interest to scout every area as you find items that can increase the capability of your Estus Flask (the main healing item) by letting you carry more charges and making it heal for more lifepoints.  The checkpoints in the game replenish your Estus Flask charges and restore all LP and revert any debuff you had prior to interaction, it also respawns enemies in the area (except minibosses).  Dark Souls III compared to  the first game is quite linear when it comes to level design but it still delivers on creating an environment that would appear to have functioned a lot of time ago.  If anything in this sounded interesting you might want to give the game a shot (I do recommend both DLCs but if you only were to get a single one, get the ringed city). Similar games worth checking out: Dark Souls, Nioh, Surge 1/2, Code Vein", "appid": "374320", "steamid": "profiles/76561198075945948", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1569672000.0}
