{"text": "I have somewhere between 50-70h in this game (on smartphone+steam). 4 created vaults, 3 were on android, one was on a pc/steam. I was playing Fallout Shelter from time to time since it was released. Each time when i was giving this \"game\" another go i was getting to the point when i end up asking myself, especially after reaching mid-game to early end-game stage: \"Why do i even bother \"playing\" this?\" Beginnings are quite decent. Planning how to build the few first layers of your vault so that you can benefit from built rooms for as long as possible before you're going to demolish them in order to build more advanced rooms in those spots, sending few first dwellers into the wastelands and for quests, \"making\" more dwellers, etc After like 10th quest you realise that they feel more like annoying chores and enjoyment from doing them fades away. You're just going through that 20-30 room vault/building doing the same thing over and over, almost every quest:  1. enter the room,  2. watch how your dwellers fight foes,  3. try not to fall asleep while watching that \"super entertaining fight\",  4. \"oh no, Jack's health is getting low, better click on that stimpack asap, there we go, such excitement, such action, such immersive gameplay, 5. Finally, fight is over, let's proceed to another room, go back to point 1. *yawn* You failed to rush a room with 3 dwellers and got attacked by a Radscorpion? That's ok, just drag quickly other dwellers from neighbouring room to help fighting. What's that? Since you're in a hurry to kill that radscorpion - you tried to quickly click and drag those dwellers but after like 3-4 tries you still failed to 'grab' them? Oh you need to \"aim\" with your mouse on that tiny spot around their legs until that green border appears to grab them (because apparently Bethesda won't bother to fix/patch such annoying bug). You lost too much time with that and radscorpion already moved to some empty room? Heh, good luck, by the time when your dwellers get there, it will move to another room while still draining your power because \"We had to make the game harder somehow\" - Bethesda. Yep, very good mechanic, makes a lot of sense /s. You got struck by sudden fire in one of your empty rooms? Better start sending half of your vault to all neighbouring rooms (of the one where fire started) because by the time when they would get to the room where the fire started - it's gonna vanish and spread too every neighbouring one. I'm talking about cases where we have few empty rooms right next to each other in some sections of our vault (like living quarters, storage rooms, etc) and dwellers have to use elevator to get there. Another thing is microtransactions. What is the point of having them when you can simply change time/clock/date on your android device or PC and 'skip' to the point when for example your dweller run out of stimpacks while exploring wastelands (to send him back to the vault) or reach quest destination/come back from it instantly. On PC i had to 'cut myself off' from the internet connection to avoid auto clock sync though. I feel bad for those naive people who decided to spend money on anything in this game while they could basically get most good stuff by simply playing around with changing time. Yeah yeah i have heard in various places/forums on the internet related to Fallout Shelter people going: \"Oh but we prefer not to cheat and play by the game's rules! It's your own fault that you destroyed your gameplay experience with that exploit!\" Except that you need few months to reach late end-game stage while that exploit allows to do that in 1 maybe 2 weeks at most. People really like those \"waiting games\" that much O_o? What if after 2-3 months of playing by the rules - you may simply lose your save/vault because of some random game crash and those are - according to people's (and my) experiences - not that uncommon? This game has so much wasted potential: For example why we can't have some kind of room for 'guards' where we could assign dwellers and they would react to any danger in the vault by rushing to take care of it asap (without player interaction)?  There are 2 dwellers in a room where enemies suddenly appeared? Game could send there 4 guards from nearest 'guard' room (since there can be only 6 dwellers in a single biggest room). They could move 25-50% faster than other non-guard dwellers in exchange for higher food/water consumption (fast reactions, like firefighters for example). Maybe we could build few such 'guarding' rooms and 'configure' them to: \"keep an eye only on this, this and that layer of rooms\" etc Exploring wasteland? Why we can't send few dwellers as a single group and once we encounter something hostile in the wastelands - to have some kind of turn-based fights? Or maybe a fight/exploring mechanic where we could control a single dweller (while others are following us/orders) and exploring wasteland/doing quests à la Terraria/Starbound style where we can simply use WSAD+mouse to move around, search for any goods and shoot? How about discovering various settlements in the wastelands? We could trade there and sell various wares that we produced back in our vault. Different settlemets would offer different prices for different goods etc, maybe we could even get there some more unique quests. Maybe some building-outpost feature where we could send some of our dwellers that are getting bored back in the vault to do \"stuff&things\"? How about a feature to create merchant caravans? We could assaign few well-armed dwellers and send it \"here\" or \"there\" with chances that they will sell some goods they will take with them, exchange for some more rare/valuable stuff, maybe buy some unique items/equipment? Find something? Everything would depend on the location where that caravan would head to. Again, so much wasted potential. Those are just examples of additional features Bethesda could implement to FS. It's hard to belive that this game was made by a company who made very good Elder Scrolls series. What the hell Bethesda. You ruined Fallout 4 by dumbing it down for casual gamers, released Fallout Shelter without putting much effort into its gameplay complexity and created that 'creation club' (paid mods) abomination. I'm starting to really worry about quality of the next Elder Scrolls game. You're slowly turning into another EA/Ubisoft/Activision. So yeah, this game in its current state feels incomplete and lacks a lot of interesting content/features. Not worth anybody's time. There is quite a few A LOT better F2P games <looks at Path of Exile>.", "appid": "588430", "steamid": "profiles/76561198078763063", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1517572800.0}
