{"text": "Black Mesa is a fan made remake of Half Life using the Half Life 2 engine, that was approved by Valve for sale after they apparently ballsed up their own conversion. Half Life is one of those \"classic\" games where in retrospect it's not exactly ♥♥♥♥ as such, but much of it's perception comes from being in that time and place to see it when it was new.  Because many of those things that were original back then are commonplace now, and have no wow factor when viewed through modern eyes. As a historical relic it deserves the praise for what it achieved in moving gaming forward, as a game to be played by people without nostalgia for it...*coughs* it's a bit arse.   Hey! It did   a shooter.  But, uh, the platforming is ♥♥♥♥.  And the shooting is, uh, bog-standard, which is I guess a bit of a problem for a shooter. It totally put you into the story and never forced you out of first person to follow a cut-scene, or took control from you during any narrative events.....That would be meaningful if there was much of a story going on. There isn't.   It is a \"cinematic\" experience, that aims for spectacle and ambience. Things like people being yanked into vents by unseen creatures are meant to be scary, or at least register some kind of response. There should be an atmosphere of dread and adversity, where you know you're playing a game and yet you're immersed in it anyway.  With Black Mesa it's all so basic compared to even a recent indie title, that despite a graphical overhaul it just doesn't work as involving spectacle anymore. An old game like Thief can have crude graphics and still be scary, as it's earned through a mixture of ambience and game-play mechanics.  Here the entire effect hinges on the visuals, and the \"freshness\" of the sequence, as it's only a brief bit of immersion. The problem being that neither is strong enough to succeed in doing so.    It's all rather quaint by now, and the engine in use was outdated when the project started, so by current standards it looks pretty pish. Having to load every 5 minutes is rather disruptive to what little compelling experience it has left to give. Back in 1998 this was the boss, but this mild lick of paint is not enough to really recommend it in this day and age.  It's distinctly \"meh\" as a blockbuster event, the shooting is a bit mediocre (as it always has been), and the engine should have been taken out back and shot the moment they got the green-light to sell the game. When it was just a fan made conversion it was \"cute\" (I suppose) that they were using the Half Life 2 engine to tidy up the mess Valve had made themselves of doing it. By this point it was already a bit creaky, but it was also free and had development tools, so presumably that influenced this even being made in the first place.  Taken as a paid for product that took eight years (or so?) to finally release....the grainy textures...the bumbling animations....the almost constant loading breaking up the flow.....  Yuck!  And as someone who uses a controller: this is a relatively recent game, and yet it still lacks such seemingly simple concepts as having a weapons wheel for anyone who plays that way. Switching between weapons is painfully bad here, though that's my particular bugbear as someone who finds the keyboard and mouse to be just as awkward to aim with, but is far more likely to cramp my hands. At the time of this review it's £15. The first two Metro games are £15 standard price. It's not fair in many ways to put them side by side, but not everyone can splash the cash willy nilly. If you only had £15 this is IMO not the best way to spend it.  Is it objectively bad? no, not in the slightest. I've played some ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ awful shooters, and this isn't one of them. Having said that: Does it hold up to modern standards at a time when some modest indie studios are capable of fairly dramatic encounters? nope, not in the slightest.  These days Black Mesa is the equivalent of being a made-for-tv action movie, versus the big budget mayhem of something that's had hundreds of millions of dollars spent on it. As a remake it's old hat, the emperor wearing slightly less shabby new clothes, but still looking pretty rough.  To carry on the film analogy: a lower budget movie might compensate for a lack of special effects, or creative excellence in its action, by having pithy dialogue or interesting drama to lessen the lack of hi-octane hi-jinks. You'll find none of that here, at least not to a degree where it's either super funny, or intriguing enough to smooth over the general blandness on  offer. It's passable but a bit \"meh\" in every way.  Is it scary? be real.... Is it pulse poundingly exciting?....uh, noooo.  Does it still have some massively boring bits that were massively ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ boring in the original too? yup.  The individual parts have all been done better elsewhere, and instead of getting a Michael Bay blockbuster remake you've gotten exactly what this began as - a fan made effort. That they're charging for it is not the problem, because I do respect the work that went into it. It just simply doesn't compare to newer games on newer engines, and I honestly can't recommend it. Yes - I'll no doubt get some stick for this opinion, but given the choice between playing a remake of the hallowed Half Life, or something like, ooh, lemme bring out \"da big gunz\" here, Titanfall 2 maybe, The Metro games, or a fun little gem like Singularity, I would never choose this.  It's clunky in it's technology and game-play, is totally lacking in atmosphere as a result of both, and is not particularly compelling as a narrative. It was the jack of all trades back in the day, but by virtue of being better than anyone else that made it a master at the time.  20 odd years later this is pish compared to the likes of Metro, which is fun in the shooty-shooty-bang-bang, scary in it's scares, and makes better \"cinematic\" use of the first person POV. Admittedly the story-telling is a load of old arse, but Black Mesa / Half Life aren't all that great in that department either. One last thing to put this in perspective: I actually did play this way back when, on the ps2, and even from a position of nostalgic affection I can see it doesn't cut the mustard in 2020. If you found this review to be helpful, then why not check out my curators page:", "appid": "362890", "steamid": "profiles/76561198250544676", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "5", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1605700800.0}
