{"text": "The game is overall fine as a nostalgia trip and time killer (during travel or other)  Sadly as a core game it is full of flaws and the main one is the pay to win factor, if you want to stay  competitive in pvp you must buy the newest packs and watch out for the meta builds online.  As a pure nostalgia trip you can allow yourself to sink some time and you don't event need to pay money to enjoy it the core old cards from the first 3 generations can be acquired via packs bought with gems - how do you acquire gems,  well that's simple level up the different characters and be active in the evens (which happen on a regular cycle excluding pvp events ofc.)   That being said after a ridiculously long time and some RNG luck you will have those nostalgia decks. And here is where the fun ends the more you progress through the stages missions(also as source of gems and resources) the more  the fixed NPC's around the game world will advance - their cards will upgrade. At one point you find yourself vs NPC with medium level decks from the latest possible cards which will destroy you if you don't fork over cash or gems. And here the nostalgia fun ends.  - Additional - these decks are short builds meaning burst and get it over with - unlike classics decks with 30 cards which quickly become outdated and the player's c***ed - Field size is limited compared to the original game (personal gripe/complaint - may vary from user to user) In conclusion waste your time at your own peril on this ''product'' - you can have some nostalgia fun but my advice is if you arrive at content after Yu-gi-oh GX dont bother and save yourself the frustration.", "appid": "601510", "steamid": "profiles/76561198051496029", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1601812800.0}
