{"text": "Update: I've more than doubled my time now in an attempt to give RoR2 a chance. But I simply don't like the direction it's going in. It feels like this was probably a much better game before 1.0. I think a lot of its appeal was the fact it didn't ask too much of the player. It didn't ask you to play for an entire hour in order to \"complete\" a run. It asked you to play for as long as you wanted, to do your best, and if you achieved a god run, congratulations. In that way, it was very balanced. But Mithrix really spoils the experience. I've beaten him on Rainstorm and have reached him by myself on Monsoon. These runs have taught me that Mithrix is not only a poorly designed boss with terrible AI, but he's pretty easy. The problem is that I just have no drive to continue learning the game and finish it on Monsoon. There's no reward for doing so beyond an achievement. The dominant strategy right now is to farm the Void during a Monsoon run, and that thought alone saps my energy. Even during the Mithrix fight, I'm always half-inclined to let him kill me because I'm bored. He takes a long time to kill, fatigue sets in, and I've done the \"kill the overpowered boss\" thing so many times in other games. It kind of just leaves me sad. The game design is so bad on so many levels. --- I'm not sure why no one's talked about the mountain of design flaws in this game. RoR2 does this thing where it can't kill you, but it keeps raising a boss' health so that you can't win. The best strategy is to get good items and DPS race everything. This wouldn't be so bad, but it's compounded with other problems that make the game amateurish and pointless. When faced with the reality that players could kite infinitely and not really be in danger, these developers thought the solution was to bloat enemy health to an absurd degree so that players go into the menu and quit out of boredom. If you don't RNG into good DPS items, it ends the run. Enemies spawn on top of you (often silently), attack you instantly, have a lot of health, swarm you, never stop, and also surround the boss in such a way that it can, at times, be impossible to target said boss with weapons that have auto-aim or lock-on, like the Huntress' bow or the Engineer's missile launcher. It does the same things a lot of other bad horde shooters do, but it's more egregious here. And to balance this out, nothing does any damage to you. Nothing can hit you. Nothing can catch up to you. Except for when the game forces you to take damage by hitting you from way off-screen with half a dozen tracking projectiles. Sometimes these do no meaningful damage, sometimes they'll kill you outright, but much of the time you'll take enough damage that it ruins your momentum and makes you wait to regenerate HP. Either kill me or let me win, but don't insult me by wasting my time. The controversy around the Captain and Mithrix highlights how wrong Hopoo's approach and design philosophies are. They really need to ask themselves what they're trying to teach with their game design, what they want to reward, and what they should punish. Because punishing people for being able to survive is silly, and a boss that can magically and infinitely heal all of its HP is operating on the same level as a child with an everything-proof shield (thanks, Yahtzee, for ruining this analogy for the rest of us). The design is confused. It doesn't teach anyone anything because it doesn't reward you for doing anything right. It rewards enduring its childish rule-bending.", "appid": "632360", "steamid": "profiles/76561198047561118", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1597752000.0}
